5000|$|... "Flexible death benefit" [...] {{means the}} policy owner {{can choose to}} {{decrease}} the <b>death</b> <b>benefit.</b> The <b>death</b> <b>benefit</b> can also be increased by the policy owner, usually requiring new underwriting. Another feature of flexible <b>death</b> <b>benefit</b> {{is the ability to}} choose option A or option B death benefits and to change those options {{over the course of the}} life of the insured. Option A is often referred to as a [...] "level death benefit"; death benefits remain level for the life of the insured, and premiums are lower than policies with Option B death benefits, which pay the policy's cash value—i.e., a face amount plus earnings/interest. If the cash value grows over time, the death benefits do too. If the cash value declines, the <b>death</b> <b>benefit</b> also declines. Option B policies normally feature higher premiums than option A policies.|$|E
